{
  "stem": "71.3",
  "chunk_idx": 7,
  "model": "openai/gpt-oss-120b",
  "elapsed_s": 9.7,
  "sentences_input": [
    {
      "segment_idx": 39,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 2,
      "text": "So when I came out, and I stood outside-- because he turned you around and looked over and told me to go in the-- I think was the right hand side-- and I-- Do you remember him?",
      "word_count": 37
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 39,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 3,
      "text": "Do you remember his face?",
      "word_count": 5
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 40,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 0,
      "text": "Yes.",
      "word_count": 1
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 40,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 1,
      "text": "Yes.",
      "word_count": 1
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 40,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 2,
      "text": "Yes.",
      "word_count": 1
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 41,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 0,
      "text": "I remember his dark eyes.",
      "word_count": 5
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 41,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 1,
      "text": "And I said to myself, if-- if he would stay in a line, the Germans would gladly take him out as a Jew because he had a very dark complexion and dark hair and brown eyes.",
      "word_count": 36
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 41,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 2,
      "text": "And I remember distinctly the-- the thought of it because my little sister, when she went to the line to get some butter, when we were sitting in Lodz before the ghetto, she was always taken out-- the German soldiers used take her out from the line and say, you little girl, you don't have to stay line, you are an Aryan.",
      "word_count": 62
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 41,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 3,
      "text": "And they used to lead her into the room to get whatever, you know, the ration was that time.",
      "word_count": 19
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 41,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 4,
      "text": "So in a-- when I looked at him, I says, he looks probably more Jewish than I do-- of course, not the nose, apparently.",
      "word_count": 24
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 41,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 5,
      "text": "But I waited and waited and my eyes [INAUDIBLE] went out till my second sister came out and we hugged and kissed.",
      "word_count": 22
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 41,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 6,
      "text": "And then the third one, Ruth, that lives over here, it took her a long-- an awful long time to come out, and we thought already, God forbid if she's not on the other side or she jumped over or whatever.",
      "word_count": 41
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 42,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 0,
      "text": "We knew-- we knew that they were sending out from Auschwitz.",
      "word_count": 11
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 42,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 1,
      "text": "We did not know where.",
      "word_count": 5
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 42,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 2,
      "text": "And we also did not know which side goes where.",
      "word_count": 10
    }
  ],
